data.name: label4.Text
data.value:
1. Respect others' workspace: Keep noise levels low and maintain a quiet environment to ensure everyone can focus.
2. No food or drinks near the computers: Spills can cause serious damage to equipment, so it's essential to keep all food and beverages away from the computers.
3. Log out when finished: Always log out of your accounts and shut down the computer properly when you're done using it to protect your privacy and the security of the network.
4. Follow software guidelines: Only use software that is permitted and properly licensed on the computers. Unauthorized software can compromise security and lead to system instability.
5. Keep workstations tidy: Clean up after yourself by disposing of any trash and organizing cables to prevent tripping hazards and maintain a professional-looking workspace.
6. Respect equipment: Treat computers, keyboards, mice, and other peripherals with care. Report any malfunctioning equipment to the lab supervisor immediately.
7. No unauthorized downloads: Downloading files or software without permission can introduce viruses, malware, or illegal content into the network. Only download files from trusted sources with approval.
8. Stay on task: Use the lab computers for educational or research purposes only. Avoid visiting non-academic websites or engaging in activities unrelated to your coursework while in the lab.
9. Respect intellectual property: Do not engage in plagiarism or unauthorized use of copyrighted materials while using lab resources. Properly cite sources and obtain permission before using others' work.
10. Be mindful of others' privacy: Avoid peeking at others' screens or disrupting their work. Respect their privacy and focus on your own tasks while in the computer lab.
